Title:
Temporal-Behavioural Detections & Whitelists (Microsoft Defender)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post documents an observed “temporal” caching effect in Microsoft Defender (Defender for Individuals and MDE) where behavioral verdicts appear to persist across subsequent executions of similar process behavior.  
- The author shows that after a successful LSASS dump using a “deconditioning” variant (string obfuscation, anti-emulation, and dumping non-critical processes first), a “standard” variant may also run without behavioral blocking shortly afterward.  
- Once a behavioral alert is triggered (e.g., by moving the binary to a non-excluded directory), Defender begins blocking/hanging subsequent executions, and this “known bad behavior” classification seems to apply across variants of the same tool.  
- The post suggests the cache decays over time (~1 hour) and notes that disabling “send samples to Microsoft” and Cloud Delivered Protection can affect repeatability and cross-system correlation via metadata.  
- Useful for red teamers and security researchers doing EDR evaluation/reproducible testing, and for defenders to understand potential statefulness and test-environment pitfalls.

Technical Focus:
- Microsoft Defender/MDE behavioral detection statefulness (temporal caching)
- LSASS dumping behavior and runtime blocking/hanging
- Deconditioning strategies (pre-dumps, anti-emulation, string obfuscation)
- Defender exclusions and their impact on runtime vs file-based actions
- Cloud Delivered Protection and local/cloud metadata correlation

Use Cases:
- Reproducing Defender behavioral detections reliably in lab testing
- Designing EDR bypass experiments while accounting for cached verdicts
- Building test harnesses/VM reset workflows for malware/EDR research
- Understanding why “variant A affects variant B” outcomes occur during iterative testing

Keywords:
Microsoft Defender, Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, MDE, behavioral detection, temporal cache, whitelist, known-bad behavior, LSASS dump, credential dumping, anti-emulation, string obfuscation, deconditioning, Defender exclusions, Cloud Delivered Protection, sample submission, metadata correlation, EDR testing, EDR introspection, DetonatorAgent